==Other versions of the legendarium==
===Early legendarium===
In the early version of the [[legendarium]], according to ''[[The Book of Lost Tales]]'', the character that would later become known as ''Ingwë'' was called '''Inwë'''.<ref name="Com">{{LT1|In}}, p. 26</ref>

Inwë was one of the three Elves (the other two being [[Finwë]] and [[Tinwë]]) that volunteered to go with [[Nornorë]], the messenger of the [[Valar]], to [[Valinor]], after their discovery at [[Koivië-néni]] - for [[Manwë]] wished to learn about their "coming" and their "desires".<ref>{{LT1|V}}, p. 115</ref>

When Inwë arrived to Valinor, he was filled with wonder and longing for the light of [[Laurelin]], one of the [[Two Trees]], and his words moved [[Yavanna]] and [[Vána]] so that they convinced most of the other Valar to summon the Elves to Valinor to live amongst them. So Inwë and the other ambassadors were sent back to Koivië-néni, and managed to convince most of the Elves to come live with the Valar.<ref>{{LT1|V}}, p. 116-8</ref>

Thereafter, Inwë became the leader of the [[Vanyar|Teleri]], the first clan of the Elves, and led them to Valinor. He was also regarded as the eldest<ref name="Dea">{{LT1|V}}, p. 129</ref> and greatest<ref>{{LT1|V}}, p. 116</ref> of all the Elves, and afterwards was considered the King of all the Eldar,<ref name="Gil">{{LT1|I}}, p. 16</ref> and his home was at the highest point in [[Kôr]], a great elven city in Valinor, which had a [[Mindon Eldaliéva#Other versions of the legendarium|silver tower]] "shooting skyward like a needle".<ref>{{LT1|V}}, p. 122</ref> The Valar also gave Inwë a seedling of one of the Two Trees, which "blossomed eternally without abating" in his court.<ref>{{LT1|V}}, p. 123</ref>

Many years later, after the [[fall of Gondolin]], the Elves of [[Kôr]] heard of the plight of the [[Gnomes]] who were enslaved by [[Melko]], and against the wishes of the Valar, Inwë led them to the [[Great Lands]] to wage war against Melko.

And even though the Elves were victorious, and Melko defeated and bound by [[Tulkas]], Inwë was, however, killed during the war.<ref name="Dea" />

After the war, with the Elves being forbidden to return to Valinor,<ref>{{LT2|VI}}, outline '''3''', p. 280</ref> Ingil his son led them from the Great Lands to [[Tol Eressëa]], the Lonely Isle, where he became their leader.<ref name="Gil" />

His kin and descendants were called the [[Inwir]], one of whom was [[Meril-i-Turinqi]] his great-granddaughter,<ref name="Dea" /> the Lady of Tol Eressëa at the time of the arrival of [[Eriol]] the Mariner, in c. [[wikipedia:5th century|5th century AD]].<ref name="Com" />

In one outline, the island of Tol Eressëa was also called ''[[Inwinórë]]'' after Inwë, but that was later changed to ''[[Ingilnórë]]'', in honour of his son Ingil instead.<ref>{{PE|12}}, p. xiii</ref> 

Inwë might have spoken [[Inwelin]], a dialect of [[Telellin]] spoken by the royal clan of Inwir.<ref>{{PE|12}}, p. 2</ref> 

====Ingwë of Luthany====
In later outlines of the ''Book of Lost Tales'', in which Tol Eressëa ceased to be identified with England, the island of [[Luthany]] appears as a precursor to England, from which the Elves of the Great Lands sail ''to'' Tol Eressëa, now a separate island.<ref>{{LT2|VI}}, pp. 300-1</ref>

In that conception of the legendarium, there appears a character called Ing or Ingwë, a [[Men|Mannish]] King of Luthany who helps and welcomes the Elves to his land, after their war with Melko and, afterwards, with unfriendly Men in the Great Lands.<ref>{{LT2|VI}}, outline '''18''', pp. 302-3</ref>

However, he is ''not'' to be identified with the character of Inwë, or that of Ingwë in the later legendarium, even though [[Christopher Tolkien]] feels there has to be some connection between the two characters.<ref>{{LT2|VI}}, outline '''21''', pp. 304-5</ref>

====Early etymology====
The name ''Inwë'' is in [[Qenya]]. In the ''[[Qenya Lexicon]]'', it is said to be derived from the root [[INI]] ("small"),<ref name="Ing">{{LT1|Appendix}}, p. 256</ref> but the earlier, original gloss of the root was "[[fairy]]".<ref>{{PE|12}}, pp. 42-3</ref>

====Other names====
The [[Gnomish]] cognate of ''Inwë'' is '''''Inwithiel''''',<ref name="Gil" /> changed from '''''Gim Githil'''''.<ref>{{LT1|I}}, Changes made to names in ''The Cottage of Lost Play'', p. 22</ref>

His proper (Gnomish) name, according to the ''[[Gnomish Lexicon]]'' was '''''Inweg''''' or '''''Im''''', with '''''Githil''''' being the Gnomish cognate of '''''Isil''''', another one of his names.<ref name="Ing" /> '''''Githiel''''' was the poetic form of ''Githil''.<ref>{{PE|11}}, p. 39</ref>

The original Gnomish form of his name was '''''Ginweg''''', later changed to '''''Gim''''' or ''Githil''.<ref>{{PE|12}}, p. xx</ref>

He was also called '''''Tur yan Eldaron''''', meaning "King of the Elves" in Qenya, with '''''Tur nan Églathon''''' being its Gnomish equivalent.<ref>{{PE|15}}, "[[Names and Required Alterations]]", ''Appendix'', ''Text VIII'', p. 16</ref>

In the ''[[Sketch of the Mythology]]'', from c. [[1926]], the name '''''Ing''''' is described as being the Gnomish form of ''Ingwë'', as opposed to the earlier conception of ''Ing'' being a rejected Qenya form of ''Inwë''.<ref>{{SM|2a}}, p. 44</ref>

